{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2259ff6d-98a4-43a7-b1e7-61567be795ef","content":"In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events** API on `Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents` in your `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* your code */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* your code */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* your code */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\nAdd this inside `CreateMauiApp()`. The `#if` directives ensure each platform block only compiles for its target. You can also hook `OnResume` (Android) / `WillEnterForeground` (iOS) for the reverse transition.\n\nDocs: [.NET MAUI app lifecycle](https://learn.microsoft.com/dotnet/maui/fundamentals/app-lifecycle)","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"81ed8046-abe9-467e-9b9b-22c3708712b2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's `OnPause`/`OnStop` and iOS's `DidEnterBackground`. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":316},"id":"a90d5fb2-04f4-494c-b1c0-ac4c7f9c15a3","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:43:58.472Z","parentId":"ea08acb5-3dcf-4d6d-adf8-ac52df9428f9"}
